## Step 4: Product Differentiation

**Key question: is the product differentiated or a commodity?**

Building on the margin (Step 2) and structure (Step 3) read, classify each major product line on the differentiation–commodity spectrum. Differentiated products command pricing power and defend margins; commodities compete on price and cost. A company can span both — assess each product type separately.

| Class | Signals | Investment Read |
|---|---|---|
| **Differentiated** | Brand premium, proprietary technology/IP, performance lead, design-wins, customization, high switching costs | Pricing power and durable margins — competes on value |
| **Semi-differentiated** | Some technical edge or brand, but credible substitutes exist | Moderate pricing power; the edge must be continually renewed |
| **Commodity** | Interchangeable specs, standardized, price is the main lever, thin margins | Cost leadership is the only edge — competes on price |

| Signal | Interpretation |
|---|---|
| Gross margin well above commodity peers, stable | Real differentiation — customers pay up |
| ASP premium vs comparable products | Brand or technology differentiation |
| Frequent price-based RFPs / spot pricing | Commodity dynamics |
| Long design-in / qualification cycles | Differentiation via switching costs |
| Product spec'd by brand vs by generic standard | Differentiated vs commodity |

**How to assess:**
- List each major product/segment from revenue segmentation.
- Check filings and transcripts for differentiation language (pricing premium, design wins, ASP, commodity).
- Cross-check Step 2 margins: differentiated products carry structurally higher, more stable gross margins than commodity peers.
- Check product reviews/benchmarks vs competitors to gauge a real performance lead.

