## Step 7: Disruption — New Entrants & New Technology

**Key question: what could reshape the industry?**

Two forces break an established structure: new entrants clearing the barriers, and new technology changing the basis of competition. Assess both.

### New Entrants

| Barrier | What Holds Entrants Out |
|---|---|
| Capital requirements | $1B+ upfront / high minimum efficient scale |
| Regulatory / licensing | Multi-year approvals (pharma, banking, telecom) |
| Technology / IP | Patents, R&D intensity, trade secrets |
| Network effects | Entrants start with zero users |
| Brand / switching costs | Customer loyalty and cost to switch |

| Entrant Signal | Interpretation |
|---|---|
| No meaningful entrant in 5+ years | High barriers — incumbents protected |
| Well-funded startups (VC-backed, $100M+) | Barriers lower than assumed — monitor |
| Adjacent tech giants entering (Amazon, Google…) | Serious threat — deep pockets, existing customers |
| New entrant already taking 5%+ in 2–3 years | Barriers were lower than expected |

### New Technology

| Tech-Disruption Signal | Interpretation |
|---|---|
| New tech substitutes the product outright | Existential — demand may migrate away entirely |
| New tech collapses the cost curve | Low-cost entrants undercut incumbents (e.g., software replacing hardware) |
| New tech shifts the business model | Value migrates (e.g., ownership → subscription, on-prem → cloud) |
| Incumbents lack the new capability in-house | High exposure — late and expensive to catch up |
| Incumbents already investing/acquiring into it | Lower exposure — adapting ahead of the curve |

**How to assess:**
- Check industry sources for entrant and technology threats (new startups, VC funding, substitutes, next-generation technology).
- Check filings and transcripts for management's view of competitive threats, barriers to entry, and technology disruption (e.g., the 10-K risk factors on competition and new technology).
- Gauge incumbent exposure: does the subject company own the new capability, or is it defending the old basis of competition?

---

## Red Flags & Green Flags

| Green Flags | Red Flags |
|---|---|
| Stable or gaining share over 3–5 years | Losing share consistently, especially to smaller players |
| Oligopoly with rational pricing | Fragmented market, no one earning above-average margins |
| Gross margin 10+ pts above median; spread widening | Margins converging with peers — moat eroding |
| High entry barriers; no entrant in 5+ years | Well-funded entrants or tech giants already taking share |
| Industry capex/revenue stable or declining | Industry-wide capex surge — capacity glut risk |
| Company owns the disruptive technology | New technology substituting or undercutting the product |

